changed extend to be extend(class, constructorargs..., def) which works with old extend(class, def) and deprecated extendContent(class, name, def) which is an alias.
pros:

backwards compatible
you now never need to use JavaAdapter unless working with interfaces
supports any number of constructor args (think planets, bullets)
also merges non-functions removing need for a.b = c over and over
cons:
none

example:
// Backwards compat alias
extendContent(Block, "name", {test(){print("i am " + this.name)}}).test();
// New variadic args stuff
extend(Block, "egg", {test(){print("i am " + this.name)}}).test();
extend(BasicBulletType, 10, 0.5, {test(){print("my dmg " + this.damage)}}).test();
// Setting variables for you - old extendContent didn't do this.
print("Speed: " + extend(UnitType, "fast", {speed: 1000}).speed);

